    "title": "Integrative Close: Efficiency in the Supply Chain",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between generation scale, transmission distance, and the physics of high-voltage efficiency.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "We have covered how electricity is generated at both large-scale power stations and through local micro-generation. We also looked at the 'Big Three' transmission voltages (400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV) and the physics behind why we use them.",
      "To bring this together, consider the journey of the energy. A large-scale gas power station might be hundreds of miles from a city, whereas a solar PV array is often right on the roof of the building using the power. This difference in distance dictates the technology and voltages required to keep the system efficient."
    ],
    "questionText": "A large-scale power station steps up its output to a transmission voltage such as 400 kV to reach a distant city, while a domestic solar PV system (micro-generation) supplies the home directly without this high-voltage step. Explain the technical reason for using such high voltages for the power station's journey and why the micro-generation system can operate efficiently without them.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "High voltage (400 kV, 275 kV, or 132 kV) is used for long-distance transmission to reduce the current (Amps).",
      "Lowering the current minimizes energy wasted as heat, known as I²R losses, which is essential when moving power over long distances.",
      "Micro-generation like solar PV is located at the point of consumption, meaning the electricity travels a very short distance and does not suffer the same significant heat losses, making high-voltage stepping unnecessary."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about the relationship between current and heat loss (I²R) over long distances versus the 'point of consumption' for micro-generation."
  }
